General Overview¶

Background:¶

Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to take advantage of the huge demand for used cars. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now.

Objective:¶

Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer), with used cars there is a huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Because of this, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market. Therefore, this project seeks to:

  1. Come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars, by building a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
  2. Explore & visualize the dataset, to show the relationship between the attributes of cars and how it affects the price of cars.
  3. Extract & generate a set of actionable insights and recommendations that can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing.

Key Questions:¶

  1. How do the different attributes such as number of seats, Fuel type, etc... affect the price of a used car?
  2. How can we significantly decrease the amount of uncertainty we have to deal with when pricing used cars.
  3. What insights & recommendations can be derived that will help the company develop the optimal pricing strategy?

Data Description:¶

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations.

The detailed data dictionary is given below:

  • S.No.:- Serial number
  • Name :- Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location :- Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  • Year :- Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven :- The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)
  • Fuel_Type :- The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission :- The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner :- Type of ownership
  • Mileage :- The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine :- The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power :- The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats :- The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price :- The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  • Price :- The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

    if df[colname].str.endswith('pl').any() or df[colname].str.endswith('kg').any() or df[colname].str.endswith('CC').any() or df[colname].str.endswith('bhp').any() or df[colname].str.endswith('Lakh').any():  
        # using `.str` to use an element-wise string method to select the required columns
        num_values.append(colname)

In [19]:
# -----------
# User defined function: This function splits the string from the numerical values in the columns
# This function will also drop the string and convert to float datatype, ensuring a cleaner and faster code
# -----------


def obj_2_num(n):
    if isinstance(n, str):  # checks if the columns are string datatype
        if n.endswith("kmpl"):
            return float(n.split("kmpl")[0])
        elif n.endswith("km/kg"):
            return float(n.split("km/kg")[0])
        elif n.endswith("CC"):
            return float(n.split("CC")[0])
        elif n.endswith("bhp"):
            return float(n.split("bhp")[0])
    else:
        return np.nan

    )  # applying above function to the column list

More Missing Value treatment¶

We have missing values in Power, Engine, Mileage and Seats. We will replace the missing values with its median value.

In [25]:
# Get the numerical columns
numeric_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()

# Replace the missing values with the median
numeric_columns.remove("Price")  # Remove the dependent variable
medianFiller = lambda x: x.fillna(x.median())
df[numeric_columns] = df[numeric_columns].apply(medianFiller, axis=0)

Outlier Treatment¶

In [59]:
# Treating outliers by flooring and capping
def outliers_treatment(df, col):

    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # All the values samller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned value of Lower_whisker
    # And all the values above upper_whishker will be assigned value of upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers(df, col_list):

    for c in col_list:
        df = outliers_treatment(df, c)

    return df

To decide if the outliers have a negative effect to the linear model, we will build a Predictive model with and without Outlier treatment and compare.

In [60]:
# Making the first copy for model 1. This will be used for the model with outlier treatment

# -----
# User Defined functions to compute adjusted R-squared
# -----
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))

# -----
# User Defined function to compute the performance of a regression model using different metrics
# -----
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
   
    mape = np.abs((target - pred)) / target * 100

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
        },
        index=[0],
    )
    
    type(r2)

    return df_perf

Insights & Recommendations¶

Key Insights & Observations¶

From the Analysis done and the Regression Model built, the following observations and key insights became evident:

  1. 5 of the most import features that determine the Price of a car are:
  • 1) Kilometers_Driven - The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)*
  • 2) Engine - The displacement volume of the engine in CC.*
  • 3) Power - The maximum power of the engine in bhp*
  • 4) New_Price - The price of a new car of the same model*
  • 5) Age_of_Car - How old the car is.*

  1. About 82% of all cars only have one previous owner. Cars with First time owner are more expensive followed by Second time owner then Third and so on. As ownership level increases, the Pricing of used cars drop.

  2. About 71% of the cars are of Manual Transmission. Transmission and Owner_type have a negative correlation to Price; ie. Manual Transmissions lower the overall Pricing of used Cars than Automatic.

  3. 84% of all cars are Five_seater

  4. About 50% of cars are sold in the South region..

  5. About 44% of cars are in Tier1 i.e at Price below 5.0 Lakhs INR.

  6. We can see that Diesel is the most Preferred Fuel_type at about 53% followed by Petrol at about 46%.CNG and LPG together make up about 1% of all cars.

  7. Electric cars have an equal Price range compared to Diesel cars.

  8. Interestingly older Tier6 cars (luxury/expensive cars) cost more than the newer ones...there is a positive correlation between Price & Age_of_Car for Tier6 cars (luxury/expensive cars) which is an exception because Price and Age are generally negatively correlated. This suggests that Tier6 cars become vintage with time.

  9. No Tier5 or Tier6 (the more expensive cars) have manual Transmission.

Recomendations to the Business¶

Based on the Predictive Model, Analysis, Insights & Observations...here are specific recommendations:

  1. Price each car at 5-10% above Predicted Price(i.e. above the Price from the Regresssion Model) because...
    (i) Psychologically speaking, starting high and letting the customer haggle the car lower will let the customer feel like they're getting a great deal.
    (ii) The Adjusted $R^2$ is approx. 95%. Meaning that 95% of the variation in Price is explained by the Independent Variables in the model. (95% Coefficient of Determination)*

  2. Offer a wide range of cars: From our Analysis, your customers have different preferences and budgets, so it's essential to offer a variety of cars to choose from. Consider stocking cars in different price ranges, makes, and models to appeal to a broader audience.

  3. We recommend that Cars4U should start an Auto Garage that maintains the cars in its inventory and offers after sales auto services & repairs to customers. This will build trust; One of the most important factors in the used car sales industry is trust. Build trust with your customers by making sure that your cars are well-maintained, and be transparent about their history, including any accidents or repairs. Also, by offering after sales service & maintenance, you give customers peace of mind (considering that used cars hardly ever have existing OEM warranties or guarantees)

  4. Develop a strong online presence and offer an online budgeting tool based on this Predictive Model: Many customers today prefer to research and shop for cars online. By having an online tool that the customer can use to forecast the price of a used car based on different configurations will help reach and convert more potential customers.

  5. Train your sales team on using this Linear Regression Model to help customers make buying decisions.

  6. We recommend that further analysis be done to segment luxury/expensive cars who's value increases with Age. Our analysis showed that certain older luxury/expensive cars cost more than the newer ones, suggesting that these cars become vintage over time. This can be a huge differentiator because older used cars generally cost lesser than newer ones. It will be great to have a used car that increases in value as it stays in your showroom.
